1. Business Need
Within the past decade the interest in Indian culture in western countries has increased exponentially. Among the various aspects of Indian culture, yoga and Indian food have seen the largest growth in interest. There is a desire for information about all things Indian but there is no centralized place to find it. IndyaVids has a vision to be a portal of knowledge on all aspects of Indian Culture by providing video guides and building an online community that can be accessed by all.

2.3 Users
There are four (4) types of users: Lurkers, Viewers, Content Creators, and Premium Content Creators, with the following hierarchy: Premium Content Creator > Content Creator > Viewer > Lurker. The actions that a Content Creator can perform subsumes the Viewer’s actions and the Premium Content Creator subsumes both of them.
Lurker: A lurker is a user that is not registered. The only actions a lurker does is watch videos. A lurker always has the option to register and become a user.

Viewer: A viewer is a registered user that primarily watches Videos. Viewers are able to rate, comment and save videos, make friends and interact with the community. It is estimated that 80% of all registered users will fall into this category.

Content Creator:  A content creator is a viewer that occasionally create videos to share with others.  Content Creators are considered to be novices in their field and are expected to create less than 3 videos per month. An estimated 10% of all users will fall into this category.

Premium Content Creators are individuals that are experts in their field and may have a pre-existing brand and fan base. They are expected to create more than 3 high quality videos per month. An estimated 10% of all users will fall into this category.

2.6 Who Cares About Indyavids
People in the United States are continually gaining interest in the Indian culture, this is an untapped market in people since no specific website was done before. This site could be one of the first to tap the billion dollar market that it is worth.

3. Statement of Work
	Recently, Indyavids released their website to the public. To reach a wider audience, the management for Indyavids believes that a mobile application would be crucial. Creative Dynamic has been tasked with creating a mobile application with mobile versions of all the important features from the main site.  At the end of summer, Creative Dynamic did extensive research to decide which mobile platform would be ideal to target for this mobile application. Creative Dynamic concluded that it should focus on developing the mobile application for the android platform due to its openness in terms of development tools.

4. Technical Constraints  
	The main Indyavids website was built using the PHPmotion framework with a few custom modifications. All data is stored on Indyavids servers in a MySQL database. Because the website was built using PHPmotion there are some PHP files that cannot be accessed. Our mobile application must communicate with that existing framework to get information. It is likely that we will need to add code on the server side to streamline communications between the main site and the android application.
Videos are hosted on Indyavids servers and are in .flv and .mp4 formats. The .mp4 format videos were added to support the mobile platforms since the android platform does not have the ability to play .flv videos. The mobile app will make use of the default media player included with the android platform so there may be limitations in the control of buffering since we are streaming directly from the Indyavids servers. The default player does a decent job of auto-buffering files so we will be relying on that.

7. Communication Covenant  
7.1 Project Roles  
Project Roles are to ensure that everyone in the team does a fair amount of work. The roles will alternate between team members during the project.
Social-Integration Lead - This position requires research in social integration of the Indyavids site. To find out the optimized method, various testings are required.
Gamification Lead - This role emphasizes on the research and evaluation of gamification. The team needs to design a gamification specifically for Indyavids and also implement for the later release.  No longer needed.
Project Leader - The Project Leader is in charge of organizing the meetings together. He will make sure that the team’s calendar is regularly updated with meeting dates, project deadlines, scheduled interviews and project milestones.
Notetaker - The Notetaker will write/type notes during team and company meetings, interviews, and whenever it is necessary. These notes should be made accessible to the Organizer.
Organizer - The Organizer will compile information from notes and 	documents and turn them into a presentable form. If there is a PowerPoint presentation needed, he will be the one in charge of completing it.
Moderator - During team and company meetings, the Moderator makes sure that all the necessary topics are covered. He will ask questions to help simulate the flow of ideas. It is his job to make sure that the meeting’s objectives are met.


7.2 Meetings
90 minutes meeting every Wednesday at 2:00pm in The Bunker, UC Irvine

7.3 Communication Tools
Each member should check these tools at least once a day so they can be updated on the project.
Email (personal and company)
Facebook
Cell Phone
Google Docs
Instant Messaging

7.4 Availability
	Each group member is expected to be able to meet during the allocated meeting times. 	Also, each group member needs to address their time conflicts at least 24 hours in advance through email or Facebook.
7.5 Code of Conduct
Conduct between group members will be friendly yet professional. Aggressive and ungentlemanly behavior will not be accepted.
7.6 Decisions
The best interest of the group will be taken into consideration in every decision 	that is agreed upon. If the group can not come to a consensus, decisions will be made by group votes. The project leader has the final call on the decision, if a decision cannot be determined by group votes.
7.7 Penalties
If a group member is 15 minutes late, he has to bring snacks for everyone at the next meetings.
If a group member does not show up to a meeting, he has to organize the next meeting and bring snacks.
If a group member continues to be tardy to our meetings, our group will have to discuss this issue with Professor Olson or Professor Ziv to find a resolution.

A Communication Covenant is an agreement every member of a team makes about communicating: 
·  	promising to communicate regularly (even when the news is bad),
·  	promising to answer your email how many times a day,
·  	agreeing that you will be using Google Docs for file management,
·  	specifying when and where your meetings are (1-2 times a week),
·  	promising to notify team mates if you can’t make a meeting,
·  	agreeing to reasonable punishments if a team mate is late or misses without notifying everyone,
·  	promising to volunteer to do things and to do them well and on time.
Conduct between group members will be friendly yet professional. Aggressive and inappropriate behavior will not be accepted.
